# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacteroides
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacteroides/acetate] An **acetate** is a salt formed by the combination of acetic acid with a base (e.g. alkaline, earthy, metallic, nonmetallic, or radical base).
[src:bacteroides/acetate] "Acetate" also describes the conjugate base or ion (specifically, the negatively charged ion called an anion) typically found in aqueous solution and written with the chemical formula C 2H 3O− 2.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] The neutral molecules formed by the combination of the acetate ion and a *positive* ion (called a cation) are also commonly called "acetates" (hence, *acetate of lead*, *acetate of aluminium*, etc.).
[src:bacteroides/acetate] The simplest of these is hydrogen acetate (called acetic acid) with corresponding salts, esters, and the polyatomic anion CH 3CO− 2, or CH 3COO− .
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Most of the approximately 5 million tonnes of acetic acid produced annually in industry are used in the production of acetates, which usually take the form of polymers.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] In nature, acetate is the most common building block for biosynthesis.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] When part of a salt, the formula of the acetate ion is written as CH 3CO− 2, C 2H 3O− 2, or CH 3COO− .
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Chemists often represent acetate as OAc− or, less commonly, AcO−.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Thus, HOAc is the symbol for acetic acid, NaOAc for sodium acetate, and EtOAc for ethyl acetate (as Ac is common symbol for acetyl group CH3CO).
[src:bacteroides/acetate] The pseudoelement symbol "Ac" is also sometimes encountered in chemical formulas as indicating the entire acetate ion (CH 3CO− 2).
[src:bacteroides/acetate] It is not to be confused with the symbol of actinium, the first element of the actinide series; context guides disambiguation.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] For example, the formula for sodium acetate might be abbreviated as "NaOAc", rather than "NaC2H3O2".
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Care should also be taken to avoid confusion with peracetic acid when using the OAc abbreviation; for clarity and to avoid errors when translated, HOAc should be avoided in literature mentioning both compounds.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Although its systematic name is *ethanoate* (/ɪˈθænoʊ.eɪt/), the common *acetate* remains the preferred IUPAC name.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] The acetate anion, [CH3COO]−,(or [C2H3O2]−) is one of the carboxylate family.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] It is the conjugate base of acetic acid.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Many acetate salts are ionic, indicated by their tendency to dissolve well in water.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Transition metals can be complexed by acetate.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Examples of acetate complexes include chromium(II) acetate and many other transition metal carboxylate complexes.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Commercially important acetate salts are aluminium acetate, used in dyeing, ammonium acetate, a precursor to acetamide, and potassium acetate, used as a diuretic.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] All three salts are colourless and highly soluble in water.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Acetate esters have the general formula CH3CO2R, where R is an organyl group.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] The esters are the dominant forms of acetate in the marketplace.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Unlike the acetate salts, acetate esters are often liquids, lipophilic, and sometimes volatile.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] They are popular because they have inoffensive, often sweet odors, they are inexpensive, and they are usually of low toxicity.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Almost half of acetic acid production is consumed in the production of vinyl acetate, precursor to polyvinyl alcohol, which is a component of many paints.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] The second largest use of acetic acid is consumed in the production of cellulose acetate.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] In fact, "acetate" is jargon for cellulose acetate, which is used in the production of fibres or diverse products, e.g. the acetate discs used in audio record production.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Cellulose acetate can be found in many household products.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Many industrial solvents are acetates, including methyl acetate, ethyl acetate, isopropyl acetate, and ethylhexyl acetate.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Butyl acetate is a fragrance used in food products.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] It is mainly utilized by organisms in the form of acetyl coenzyme A.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Intraperitoneal injection of sodium acetate (20 or 60 mg per kg body mass) was found to induce headache in sensitized rats, and it has been proposed that acetate resulting from oxidation of ethanol is a major factor in causing hangovers.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Increased serum acetate levels lead to accumulation of adenosine in many tissues including the brain, and administration of the adenosine receptor antagonist caffeine to rats after ethanol was found to decrease nociceptive behavior.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Acetate has known immunomodulatory properties and can affect the innate immune response to pathogenic bacteria such as the respiratory pathogen *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Pyruvate is converted into acetyl-coenzyme A (acetyl-CoA) by the enzyme pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] This acetyl-CoA is then converted into acetate in *E. coli*, whilst producing ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] Acetate formation requires two enzymes: phosphate acetyltransferase and acetate kinase.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] This disproportionation reaction is catalysed by methanogen archaea in their fermentative metabolism.
[src:bacteroides/acetate] One electron is transferred from the carbonyl function (e− donor) of the carboxylic group to the methyl group (e− acceptor) of acetic acid to respectively produce CO2 and methane gas.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:bacteroides/actinomycetota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Previously treated as being hormonally inert, in recent years adipose tissue has been recognized as a major endocrine organ, as it produces hormones such as leptin, estrogen, resistin, and cytokines (especially TNFα).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In obesity, adipose tissue is implicated in the chronic release of pro-inflammatory markers known as adipokines, which are responsible for the development of metabolic syndrome—a constellation of diseases including type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease and atherosclerosis.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is derived from preadipocytes and its formation appears to be controlled in part by the adipose gene.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The two types of adipose tissue are white adipose tissue (WAT), which stores energy, and brown adipose tissue (BAT), which generates body heat.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue—more specifically brown adipose tissue—was first identified by the Swiss naturalist Conrad Gessner in 1551.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In humans, adipose tissue is located beneath the skin (subcutaneous fat), around internal organs (visceral fat), in bone marrow (yellow bone marrow), intermuscular (muscular system), and in the breast (breast tissue).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is found in specific locations, which are referred to as *adipose depots*.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In addition to adipocytes, which comprise the highest percentage of cells within adipose tissue, other cell types are present, collectively termed stromal vascular fraction (SVF) of cells.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] SVF includes preadipocytes, fibroblasts, adipose tissue macrophages, and endothelial cells.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue contains many small blood vessels.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In the integumentary system, which includes the skin, it accumulates in the deepest level, the subcutaneous layer, providing insulation from heat and cold.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Around organs, it provides protective padding.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Adipose depots in different parts of the body have different biochemical profiles.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Under normal conditions, it provides feedback for hunger and diet to the brain.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In an obese person, excess adipose tissue hanging downward from the abdomen is referred to as a panniculus.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] A panniculus complicates surgery of the morbidly obese individual.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] It may remain as a literal "apron of skin" if a severely obese person loses large amounts of fat (a common result of gastric bypass surgery).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Obesity is treated through exercises, diet, behavioral therapy, and liposuctions.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Reconstructive surgery is one aspect of treatment.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat or abdominal fat (also known as organ fat or intra-abdominal fat) is located inside the abdominal cavity, packed between the organs (stomach, liver, intestines, kidneys, etc.).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is different from subcutaneous fat underneath the skin, and intramuscular fat interspersed in skeletal muscles.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Fat in the lower body, as in thighs and buttocks, is subcutaneous and is not consistently spaced tissue, whereas fat in the abdomen is mostly visceral and semi-fluid.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is composed of several adipose depots, including mesenteric, epididymal white adipose tissue (EWAT), and perirenal depots.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat is often expressed in terms of its area in cm2 (VFA, visceral fat area).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] An excess of visceral fat is known as abdominal obesity, or "belly fat", in which the abdomen protrudes excessively.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] New developments such as the Body Volume Index (BVI) are specifically designed to measure abdominal volume and abdominal fat.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Excess visceral fat is also linked to type 2 diabetes, insulin resistance, inflammatory diseases, and other obesity-related diseases.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Likewise, the accumulation of neck fat (or cervical adipose tissue) has been shown to be associated with mortality.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Several studies have suggested that visceral fat can be predicted from simple anthropometric measures, and predicts mortality more accurately than body mass index or waist circumference.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Men are more likely to have fat stored in the abdomen due to sex hormone differences.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Estrogen (female sex hormone) causes fat to be stored in the buttocks, thighs, and hips in women.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] When women reach menopause and the estrogen produced by the ovaries declines, fat migrates from the buttocks, hips and thighs to the waist; later fat is stored in the abdomen.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Visceral fat can be caused by excess cortisol levels.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] At least 10 MET-hours per week of aerobic exercise leads to visceral fat reduction in those without metabolic-related disorders.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Resistance training and caloric restriction also reduce visceral fat, although their effect may not be cumulative.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Both exercise and hypocaloric diet cause loss of visceral fat, but exercise has a larger effect on visceral fat versus total fat.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] High-intensity exercise is one way to effectively reduce total abdominal fat.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] An energy-restricted diet combined with exercise will reduce total body fat and the ratio of visceral adipose tissue to subcutaneous adipose tissue, suggesting a preferential mobilization for visceral fat over subcutaneous fat.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Epicardial adipose tissue (EAT) is a particular form of visceral fat deposited around the heart and found to be a metabolically active organ that generates various bioactive molecules, which might significantly affect cardiac function.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Marked component differences have been observed in comparing EAT with subcutaneous fat, suggesting a location-specific impact of stored fatty acids on adipocyte function and metabolism.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Most of the remaining nonvisceral fat is found just below the skin in a region called the hypodermis.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] This subcutaneous fat is not related to many of the classic obesity-related pathologies, such as heart disease, cancer, and stroke, and some evidence even suggests it might be protective.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The typically female (or gynecoid) pattern of body fat distribution around the hips, thighs, and buttocks is subcutaneous fat, and therefore poses less of a health risk compared to visceral fat.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Like all other fat organs, subcutaneous fat is an active part of the endocrine system, secreting the hormones leptin and resistin.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The relationship between the subcutaneous adipose layer and total body fat in a person is often modelled by using regression equations.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The most popular of these equations was formed by Durnin and Wormersley, who rigorously tested many types of skinfold, and, as a result, created two formulae to calculate the body density of both men and women.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] These equations present an inverse correlation between skinfolds and body density—as the sum of skinfolds increases, the body density decreases.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Factors such as sex, age, population size or other variables may make the equations invalid and unusable, and, as of 2012, Durnin and Wormersley's equations remain only estimates of a person's true level of fatness.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Marrow fat, also known as marrow adipose tissue (MAT), is a poorly understood adipose depot that resides in the bone and is interspersed with hematopoietic cells as well as bony elements.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The adipocytes in this depot are derived from mesenchymal stem cells (MSC) which can give rise to fat cells, bone cells as well as other cell types.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The fact that MAT increases in the setting of calorie restriction/ anorexia is a feature that distinguishes this depot from other fat depots.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Exercise regulates MAT, decreasing MAT quantity and diminishing the size of marrow adipocytes.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The exercise regulation of marrow fat suggests that it bears some physiologic similarity to other white adipose depots.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Moreover, increased MAT in obesity further suggests a similarity to white fat depots.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Ectopic fat is the storage of triglycerides in tissues other than adipose tissue, that are supposed to contain only small amounts of fat, such as the liver, skeletal muscle, heart, and pancreas.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] This can interfere with cellular functions and hence organ function and is associated with insulin resistance in type-2 diabetes.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] It is stored in relatively high amounts around the organs of the abdominal cavity, but is not to be confused with visceral fat.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The specific cause for the accumulation of ectopic fat is unknown.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The cause is likely a combination of genetic, environmental, and behavioral factors that are involved in excess energy intake and decreased physical activity.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Substantial weight loss can reduce ectopic fat stores in all organs and this is associated with an improvement of the function of those organs.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In the latter case, non-invasive weight loss interventions like diet or exercise can decrease ectopic fat (particularly in heart and liver) in overweight or obese children and adults.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Free fatty acids (FFAs) are liberated from lipoproteins by lipoprotein lipase (LPL) and enter the adipocyte, where they are reassembled into triglycerides by esterifying them onto glycerol.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Human fat tissue contains from 61% to 94% lipids.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Lean and obese individuals tend towards the low and high ends of this range, respectively.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] There is a constant flux of FFAs entering and leaving adipose tissue.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The net direction of this flux is controlled by insulin and leptin—if insulin is elevated, then there is a net inward flux of FFA, and only when insulin is low can FFA leave adipose tissue.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Insulin secretion is stimulated by high blood sugar, which results from consuming carbohydrates.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In humans, lipolysis (hydrolysis of triglycerides into free fatty acids) is controlled through the balanced control of lipolytic B-adrenergic receptors and a2A-adrenergic receptor-mediated antilipolysis.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Fat cells have an important physiological role in maintaining triglyceride and free fatty acid levels, as well as determining insulin resistance.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Abdominal fat has a different metabolic profile—being more prone to induce insulin resistance.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] This explains to a large degree why central obesity is a marker of impaired glucose tolerance and is an independent risk factor for cardiovascular disease (even in the absence of diabetes mellitus and hypertension).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Recent advances in biotechnology have allowed for the harvesting of adult stem cells from adipose tissue, allowing stimulation of tissue regrowth using a patient's own cells.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In addition, adipose-derived stem cells from both human and animals reportedly can be efficiently reprogrammed into induced pluripotent stem cells without the need for feeder cells.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The use of a patient's own cells reduces the chance of tissue rejection and avoids ethical issues associated with the use of human embryonic stem cells.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] A growing body of evidence also suggests that different fat depots (i.e. abdominal, omental, pericardial) yield adipose-derived stem cells with different characteristics.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] These depot-dependent features include proliferation rate, immunophenotype, differentiation potential, gene expression, as well as sensitivity to hypoxic culture conditions.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Oxygen levels seem to play an important role on the metabolism and in general the function of adipose-derived stem cells.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue is a major peripheral source of aromatase in both males and females, contributing to the production of estradiol.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissues also secrete a type of cytokines (cell-to-cell signalling proteins) called adipokines (adipose cytokines), which play a role in obesity-associated complications.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Perivascular adipose tissue releases adipokines such as adiponectin that affect the contractile function of the vessels that they surround.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Brown fat or brown adipose tissue (BAT) is a specialized form of adipose tissue important for adaptive thermogenesis in humans and other mammals.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] BAT can generate heat by "uncoupling" the respiratory chain of oxidative phosphorylation within mitochondria through tissue-specific expression of uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] BAT is primarily located around the neck and large blood vessels of the thorax, where it may effectively act in heat exchange.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] BAT is robustly activated upon cold exposure by the release of catecholamines from sympathetic nerves that results in UCP1 activation.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Nearly half of the nerves present in adipose tissue are sensory neurons connected to the dorsal root ganglia.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] BAT activation may also occur in response to overfeeding.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] UCP1 activity is stimulated by long chain fatty acids that are produced subsequent to β-adrenergic receptor activation.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] UCP1 is proposed to function as a fatty acid proton symporter, although the exact mechanism has yet to be elucidated.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In contrast, UCP1 is inhibited by ATP, ADP, and GTP.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Attempts to simulate this process pharmacologically have so far been unsuccessful.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Techniques to manipulate the differentiation of "brown fat" could become a mechanism for weight loss therapy in the future, encouraging the growth of tissue with this specialized metabolism without inducing it in other organs.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] A review on the eventual therapeutic targeting of brown fat to treat human obesity was published by Samuelson and Vidal-Puig in 2020.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Until recently, brown adipose tissue in humans was thought to be primarily limited to infants, but new evidence has overturned that belief.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Metabolically active tissue with temperature responses similar to brown adipose was first reported in the neck and trunk of some human adults in 2007, and the presence of brown adipose in human adults was later verified histologically in the same anatomical regions.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Browning of WAT, also referred to as "beiging", occurs when adipocytes within WAT depots develop features of BAT.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] **Beige adipocytes** take on a multilocular appearance (containing several lipid droplets) and increase expression of uncoupling protein 1 (UCP1).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In doing so, these normally energy-storing adipocytes become energy-releasing adipocytes.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The calorie-burning capacity of brown and beige fat has been extensively studied as research efforts focus on therapies targeted to treat obesity and diabetes.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The drug 2,4-dinitrophenol, which also acts as a chemical uncoupler similarly to UCP1, was used for weight loss in the 1930s.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] However, it was quickly discontinued when excessive dosing led to adverse side effects including hyperthermia and death. β3-adrenergic agonists, like CL316,243, have also been developed and tested in humans.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] However, the use of such drugs has proven largely unsuccessful due to several challenges, including varying species receptor specificity and poor oral bioavailability.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Cold is a primary regulator of BAT processes and induces WAT browning.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Browning in response to chronic cold exposure has been well documented and is a reversible process.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] A study in mice demonstrated that cold-induced browning can be completely reversed in 21 days, with measurable decreases in UCP1 seen within a 24-hour period.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] A study by Rosenwald et al. revealed that when the animals are re-exposed to a cold environment, the same adipocytes will adopt a beige phenotype, suggesting that beige adipocytes are retained.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Transcriptional regulators, as well as a growing number of other factors, regulate the induction of beige fat.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Four regulators of transcription are central to WAT browning and serve as targets for many of the molecules known to influence this process.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] These include peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARγ), PRDM16, peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma coactivator 1 alpha (PGC-1α), and Early B-Cell Factor-2 (EBF2).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The list of molecules that influence browning has grown in direct proportion to the popularity of this topic and is constantly evolving as more knowledge is acquired.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Among these molecules are irisin and fibroblast growth factor 21 (FGF21), which have been well-studied and are believed to be important regulators of browning.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Irisin is secreted from muscle in response to exercise and has been shown to increase browning by acting on beige preadipocytes.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] FGF21, a hormone secreted mainly by the liver, has garnered a great deal of interest after being identified as a potent stimulator of glucose uptake and a browning regulator through its effects on PGC-1α.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] It is increased in BAT during cold exposure and is thought to aid in resistance to diet-induced obesity FGF21 may also be secreted in response to exercise and a low protein diet, although the latter has not been thoroughly investigated.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Data from these studies suggest that environmental factors like diet and exercise may be important mediators of browning.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In mice, it was found that beiging can occur through the production of methionine-enkephalin peptides by type 2 innate lymphoid cells in response to interleukin 33.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Due to the complex nature of adipose tissue and a growing list of browning regulatory molecules, great potential exists for the use of bioinformatics tools to improve study within this field.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Studies of WAT browning have greatly benefited from advances in these techniques, as beige fat is rapidly gaining popularity as a therapeutic target for the treatment of obesity and diabetes.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] DNA microarray is a bioinformatics tool used to quantify expression levels of various genes simultaneously, and has been used extensively in the study of adipose tissue.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] One such study used microarray analysis in conjunction with Ingenuity IPA software to look at changes in WAT and BAT gene expression when mice were exposed to temperatures of 28 and 6 °C.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The most significantly up- and downregulated genes were then identified and used for analysis of differentially expressed pathways.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] It was discovered that many of the pathways upregulated in WAT after cold exposure are also highly expressed in BAT, such as oxidative phosphorylation, fatty acid metabolism, and pyruvate metabolism.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] This suggests that some of the adipocytes switched to a beige phenotype at 6 °C.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Mössenböck et al. also used microarray analysis to demonstrate that insulin deficiency inhibits the differentiation of beige adipocytes but does not disturb their capacity for browning.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] These two studies demonstrate the potential for the use of microarray in the study of WAT browning.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] RNA sequencing (RNA-Seq) is a powerful computational tool that allows for the quantification of RNA expression for all genes within a sample.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Incorporating RNA-Seq into browning studies is of great value, as it offers better specificity, sensitivity, and a more comprehensive overview of gene expression than other methods.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] RNA-Seq has been used in both human and mouse studies in an attempt characterize beige adipocytes according to their gene expression profiles and to identify potential therapeutic molecules that may induce the beige phenotype.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] One such study used RNA-Seq to compare gene expression profiles of WAT from wild-type (WT) mice and those overexpressing Early B-Cell Factor-2 (EBF2).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] WAT from the transgenic animals exhibited a brown fat gene program and had decreased WAT specific gene expression compared to the WT mice.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Thus, EBF2 has been identified as a potential therapeutic molecule to induce beiging.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Chromatin immunoprecipitation with sequencing (ChIP-seq) is a method used to identify protein binding sites on DNA and assess histone modifications.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] This tool has enabled examination of epigenetic regulation of browning and helps elucidate the mechanisms by which protein-DNA interactions stimulate the differentiation of beige adipocytes.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Studies observing the chromatin landscapes of beige adipocytes have found that adipogenesis of these cells results from the formation of cell specific chromatin landscapes, which regulate the transcriptional program and, ultimately, control differentiation.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Using ChIP-seq in conjunction with other tools, recent studies have identified over 30 transcriptional and epigenetic factors that influence beige adipocyte development.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The thrifty gene hypothesis (also called the famine hypothesis) states that in some populations the body would be more efficient at retaining fat in times of plenty, thereby endowing greater resistance to starvation in times of food scarcity.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In 1995, Jeffrey Friedman, in his residency at the Rockefeller University, together with Rudolph Leibel, Douglas Coleman et al. discovered the protein leptin that the genetically obese mouse lacked.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Leptin is produced in the white adipose tissue and signals to the hypothalamus.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] When leptin levels drop, the body interprets this as a loss of energy, and hunger increases.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Mice lacking this protein eat until they are four times their normal size.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Leptin, however, plays a different role in diet-induced obesity in rodents and humans.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Because adipocytes produce leptin, leptin levels are elevated in the obese.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] However, hunger remains, and—when leptin levels drop due to weight loss—hunger increases.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The drop of leptin is better viewed as a starvation signal than the rise of leptin as a satiety signal.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] However, elevated leptin in obesity is known as leptin resistance.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The changes that occur in the hypothalamus to result in leptin resistance in obesity are currently the focus of obesity research.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Gene defects in the leptin gene (*ob*) are rare in human obesity.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Others have been identified as genetically partially deficient in leptin, and, in these individuals, leptin levels on the low end of the normal range can predict obesity.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Several mutations of genes involving the melanocortins (used in brain signaling associated with appetite) and their receptors have also been identified as causing obesity in a larger portion of the population than leptin mutations.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Different cell types within adipose tissue exhibit distinct DNA methylation patterns.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Mature adipocytes and adipose progenitor cells (ASPCs) show a high degree of hypomethylation, affecting more than 50% of their regulatory regions.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] This hypomethylation is associated with the activation of genes involved in triglyceride synthesis, such as glycerol‑3‑phosphate acyltransferase 1 (GPAM).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In contrast, myeloid cells display approximately 73% hypermethylated regions, reflecting an epigenetic program opposite to that of the adipocytic lineage.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Overall, there is a direct relationship between DNA demethylation and gene expression, whereby highly expressed genes tend to exhibit low methylation levels.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] These epigenetic patterns contribute to defining the functional identity of the different cell types within subcutaneous adipose tissue (SAT).
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Adipose tissue has a density of ~0.9 g/ml.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Thus, a person with more adipose tissue will float more easily than a person of the same weight with more muscular tissue, since muscular tissue has a density of 1.06 g/ml.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In addition to the visible changes in adipose tissue associated with obesity, recent research indicates that the risk of developing abdominal obesity and cardiometabolic alterations also depends on the 3D organization of the genome in subcutaneous adipose tissue.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Single‑cell epigenomic studies have shown that many genetic variants associated with abdominal fat distribution (measured as WHRadjBMI) are preferentially located in active genomic regions of adipocytes.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] These regions display low levels of DNA methylation and belong to the so‑called A compartment, which is characterized by higher gene activity.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] These findings suggest that adipocytes in subcutaneous adipose tissue play a key role in mediating the genetic risk associated with abdominal obesity.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] A **body fat meter** is a tool used to measure the body fat to weight ratio in the human body.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Different meters use various methods to determine the ratio.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] They tend to under-read body fat percentage.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] In contrast with clinical tools like DXA and underwater weighing, one relatively inexpensive type of body fat meter uses the principle of bioelectrical impedance analysis (BIA) in order to determine an individual's body fat percentage.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] To achieve this, the meter passes a small, harmless, electric current through the body and measures the resistance, then uses information on the person's weight, height, age, and sex to calculate an approximate value for the person's body fat percentage.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The calculation measures the total volume of water in the body (lean tissue and muscle contain a higher percentage of water than fat), and estimates the percentage of fat based on this information.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] The result can fluctuate several percentage points depending on what has been eaten and how much water has been drunk before the analysis.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] This method is quick and readily accessible, but imprecise.
[src:bacteroides/adipose-tissue] Alternative methods are: skin fold methods using calipers, underwater weighing, whole body air displacement plethysmography (ADP) and DXA.
[src:bacteroides/aerotolerant] There are three categories of anaerobes.
[src:bacteroides/aerotolerant] Where obligate aerobes require oxygen to grow, obligate anaerobes are damaged by oxygen, aerotolerant organisms cannot use oxygen but tolerate its presence, and facultative anaerobes use oxygen if it is present but can grow without it.
[src:bacteroides/aerotolerant] Most aerotolerant anaerobes have superoxide dismutase and (non-catalase) peroxidase but do not have catalase.
[src:bacteroides/aerotolerant] More specifically, they may use a NADH oxidase/NADH peroxidase (NOX/NPR) system or a glutathione peroxidase system.
[src:bacteroides/aerotolerant] An example of an aerotolerant anaerobe is *Cutibacterium acnes*.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] An **agar plate** is a Petri dish that contains a growth medium solidified with agar, used to culture microorganisms.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Sometimes selective compounds are added to influence growth, such as antibiotics.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Individual microorganisms placed on the plate will grow into individual colonies, each a clone genetically identical to the individual ancestor organism (except for the low, unavoidable rate of mutation).
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Thus, the plate can be used either to estimate the concentration of organisms in a liquid culture or a suitable dilution of that culture using a colony counter, or to generate genetically pure cultures from a mixed culture of genetically different organisms.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Several methods are available to plate out cells.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] In this technique, a drop of the culture on the end of a thin, sterile loop of wire, sometimes known as an inoculator, is streaked across the surface of the agar leaving organisms behind, a higher number at the beginning of the streak and a lower number at the end.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] At some point during a successful "streak", the number of organisms deposited will be such that distinct individual colonies will grow in that area which may be removed for further culturing, using another sterile loop.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Another way of plating organisms, next to streaking, on agar plates is the spot analysis.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] This type of analysis is often used to check the viability of cells and is performed with pinners (often also called froggers).
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] A third technique is using sterile glass beads to plate out cells.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] In this technique, cells are grown in a liquid culture, in which a small volume is pipetted on the agar plate and then spread out with the beads.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Replica plating is another technique used to plate out cells on agar plates.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] These four techniques are the most common, but others are also possible.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] It is crucial to work in a sterile manner to prevent contamination on the agar plates.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Plating is thus often done in a laminar flow cabinet or on the working bench next to a bunsen burner.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] In 1881, Fanny Hesse, who was working as a technician for her husband Walther Hesse in the laboratory of Robert Koch, suggested agar as an effective setting agent, since it had been commonplace in jam making for some time.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Agar plates may be formulated as either permissive, with the intent of allowing the growth of whatever organisms are present, or restrictive or selective, with the intent of only allowing the growth of a particular subset of those organisms.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] This correlates to some degree with defined and undefined media; undefined media, made from natural products and containing an unknown combination of very many organic molecules, is typically more permissive in terms of supplying the needs of a wider variety of organisms.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] In contrast, defined media can be precisely tailored to select organisms with specific properties.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Agar plates may also be indicator plates, in which the organisms are not selected based on growth, but are instead distinguished by a color change in some colonies, typically caused by the action of an enzyme on some compound added to the medium.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] The plates are incubated for 12 hours up to several days, depending on the test that is performed.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Blood agar plates (BAPs) contain mammalian blood (usually sheep or horse), typically at a 5–10% concentration.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] BAPs are enriched, and differential media is used to isolate fastidious organisms and detect hemolytic activity. β-Hemolytic activity will show lysis and complete digestion of red blood cell contents surrounding a colony.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Examples include *Streptococcus haemolyticus*. α-Hemolysis will only cause partial lysis of the red blood cells (the cell membrane is left intact) and appear green or brown due to the conversion of hemoglobin to methemoglobin.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] An example of this would be *Streptococcus viridans*. γ-Hemolysis (or non-hemolytic) is the term referring to a lack of hemolytic activity.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] BAPs also contain meat extract or yeast extract, tryptone, sodium chloride, and agar.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Chocolate agar is a type of blood agar plate in which the blood cells have been lysed by heating the cells to 80 °C.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] It is used for growing fastidious respiratory bacteria, such as *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Chocolate agar is named for its color, and no chocolate is contained in the plate.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Thayer–Martin agar is a chocolate agar designed to isolate *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* and *Neisseria meningitidis*.
[src:bacteroides/agar-plate] Thiosulfate–citrate–bile salts–sucrose agar enhances growth of *Vibrio* spp., including *Vibrio cholerae*.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] Albert John Chalmers was born in Manchester on 28 March 1870.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] He received his qualifications in 1890 at University College, Liverpool, holding the Holt Fellowship.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] He joined the West African Medical Service, where he served for four years at the Gold Coast Colony, as the assistant colonial surgeon.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] He was the acting principal medical officer in the colony during the Siege of Kumassi in 1900 when he was mentioned in despatches and subsequently received the Ashanti Medal and clasp for his service.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] He left for Ceylon in 1901 where he worked for the next ten years as the registrar and lecturer on pathology at the Colombo Medical College.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] He was a captain in the Ceylon Volunteer Medical Corps and president of the Ceylon branch of the British Medical Association in 1907.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] In 1911 he was awarded the King George V Coronation Medal.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] After serving with the Pellagra Field Commission in 1913 he was appointed as the Director of the Wellcome Tropical Research Laboratories in Khartoum.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] By then he was a well known name in tropical medicine.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] While in Colombo he co-authored with Aldo Castellani the *Manual of Tropical Medicine*, the first edition of which appeared in 1910 and was described by F.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] Garrison as “the best modern book on tropical medicine”.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] In February 1920, Chalmers turned in his resignation to the Sudan Government and left to travel the world with his wife Alice.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] While traveling in India, Chalmers fell ill and died on 5 April 1920 of acute infective jaundice.
[src:bacteroides/albert-john-chalmers] The Chalmers Memorial Medal is offered annually by the Royal Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene, in recognition of outstanding research contributing to knowledge of tropical medicine and tropical hygiene.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] Castellani was born in Florence and educated there, qualifying in medicine in 1899.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He worked for a time in Bonn and joined the School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine in London in 1901.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] As bacteriologist with the Royal Society Commission on Sleeping Sickness in 1902, he went to Entebbe, Uganda with George Carmichael Low and Cuthbert Christy.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He demonstrated the cause and means of transmission of sleeping sickness, discovered the spirochete of yaws, and did other original work in bacteriology and in parasitic diseases of the skin.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] In 1903 he was appointed Bacteriologist to the Government of Ceylon at the Central laboratory in Colombo and continued research in mycology and bacteriology, describing several new species of intestinal bacilli.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He invented the absorption test for the serological identification of closely allied organisms.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He left Ceylon in 1915 for Naples where he took the Chair of Medicine.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He was involved during World War I in Serbia and Macedonia as a member of the Inter-Allied Sanitary Commission.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] In 1919 Castellani went to London as Consultant to the Ministry of Pensions.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He became lecturer on mycology and mycotic diseases at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine (LSHTM), and established a consulting practice in Harley Street.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He was also director of tropical medicine and dermatology at the Ross Institute prior to its merger with LSHTM.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] In late 1925 he arrived in New Orleans to direct a tropical medicine department at Tulane University School of Medicine, and would travel twice yearly between New Orleans and London to work on two continents.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He was knighted in 1928 as an Honorary KCMG and in 1934 his daughter Jacqueline Castellani married Sir Miles Lampson.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] Castellani's enthusiasm for Royal and eminent patients such as Benito Mussolini clouded his reputation and during World War II he supported Italy against the Allies, becoming chief of the Italian Army's medical service.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] War correspondent Alaric Jacob discovered his looted quarters in Cirene in December 1941 and was tempted to pass his correspondence to his son in law Sir Miles Lampson, then British Ambassador in Egypt.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] Castellani was President of the International Society of Dermatology from 1960 to 1964, which he had founded in 1959.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He was also professor of tropical medicine at the State University of Louisiana and at the Royal University of Rome.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] He followed the Queen of Italy Marie José into exile in Portugal and ended his life as Professor at Lisbon's Institute of Tropical Medicine.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] Castellani's paint (Carbol fuchsin solution) is still occasionally used to treat fungal skin infections.
[src:bacteroides/aldo-castellani] The amoeba *Acanthamoeba castellanii* (Douglas, 1930) was discovered by him and later found to be an opportunistic human pathogen.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] One of the most important clinically is *Bacteroides fragilis*.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] The former *Bacteroides melaninogenicus* was reclassified and split into *Prevotella melaninogenica* and *Prevotella intermedia*.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] In general, *Bacteroides* are resistant to a wide variety of antibiotics—β-lactams, aminoglycosides, and recently many species have acquired resistance to erythromycin and tetracycline.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] This high level of antibiotic resistance has prompted concerns that *Bacteroides* species may become a reservoir for resistance in other, more highly pathogenic bacterial strains.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] It has been often considered susceptible to clindamycin, but recent evidence demonstrated an increasing trend in clindamycin resistance rates (up to 33%).
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] In cases where *Bacteroides* can move outside the gut due to gastrointestinal tract rupture or intestinal surgery, *Bacteroides* can infect several parts of the human body.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] *Bacteroides* can enter the central nervous system by penetrating the blood brain barrier through the olfactory and trigeminal cranial nerves and can cause meningitis and brain abscesses.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] *Bacteroides* has also been isolated from abscesses in the neck and lungs.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] Some *Bacteroides* species are associated with Crohn's disease, appendicitis and inflammatory bowel disease.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] *Bacteroides* species play multiple roles within the human gut microbiome.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] One study has measured the amount of *Bacteroides* by using qPCR to quantify the host-specific 16S rRNA genetic marker.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] This technique allows quantification of genetic markers that are specific to the host of the bacteria Bacteroides and allow detection of recent contamination.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] A recent report found temperature plays a major role in the amount of time the bacteria will persist in the environment, the life span increases with colder temperatures (0–4 °C).
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] "A new study has found that there is a three-way relationship between a type of gut bacteria, cortisol, and brain metabolites.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] Another study showed a 5.6-times higher risk of osteoporosis fractures in the low Bacteroides group of Japanese postmenopausal women.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] Members of the Bacillota and Bacteroidota phyla make up a majority of the bacterial species in the human intestinal microbiota (the "gut microbiome").
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] The healthy human gut microbiome consists of 109 abundant species of which 31 (19.7%) are members of the Bacteroidetes while 63 (40%) and 32 (20%) belong to Bacillota and Actinomycetota.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] There is data suggesting that members of *Bacteroides* affect the lean or obese phenotype in humans.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] In this article, one human twin is obese while the other is lean.
[src:bacteroides/bacteroides] When their fecal microbiota is transplanted into germ-free mice, the phenotype in the mouse model corresponds to that in humans.
